metadata.name: saprophyte #88
metadata.description:
saprophyte is a real-time interactive particle system based on the principles of stigmergy. 60,000  particles move around the canvas leaving trails behind them as they move, while each particle decides how to move based on the trails left by other particles around it. You can click to erase the trails in an area, forcing the particles to rebuild their structures anew.

Press "c" to capture an image. By default this will save an image at the resolution of the browser window. If you'd like to save an image at a different resolution, you can press "o" to override the browser's resolution and force the piece to render at a resolution of your choice, and then press "c" to capture the image at your chosen resolution. For best results, wait several seconds after changing the resolution to capture an image, as the piece may need time to adjust to the new resolution.

metadata.name: Down The Slope #64
metadata.description:
The viewer is given access to some information points when he chooses a viewing angle, while another part of the image is hidden from him.
The image producer arranges information points and attention centers, and by choosing a viewing angle, a few information points are prioritized and others are relegated to peripheral information or even leave the image field.
Therefore, the point of view not only allows the viewer to construct a meaning that is close to the producer's intention, but it also allows the viewer to distinguish between important and irrelevant information points.

Made by p5.js
s = save

metadata.name: Dreamscape #31
metadata.description:
As I create each artwork, my interest in circular patterns grows, so this is an exploration of combining nested circular algorithms with linear patterns. A wide variety of sizes and color palettes have been considered for this artwork.  This artwork can also be plotted in large dimensions.
_________________________

To see the artwork in high quality, open it in live view and add “&res=1 to 25” to the URL.

Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Provence #455
metadata.description:
The south of France namely the Provence has a cultural history of being an inspiration for impressionists and post-impressionists in the past.
For me personally the Provence is the place i was spending long, peaceful holidays as a child within beautiful nature.
This work does not so much aim for being realistic, rather than give an impression or feeling for this wonderful landscape. 
There are just a few different elements and concepts and yet there is variety of fascinating results.
I really hope you will enjoy your minting.

Notes:
STARTUP AND RENDERING MAY TAKE SOME TIME. (Up to 1min)
Code was written in typescript.
The only used libraries were chroma.js and simplex-noise

metadata.name: Jajim #173
metadata.description:
The main idea of the "Jajim" is to divide a square into smaller parts in such a way that each variation has its original and unique composition. The role of lines is such that sometimes they help the dynamics of the composition and sometimes they appear in the form of texture and its contrast with empty spaces leads to the visual richness of the work. I avoided drawing various visual elements in favor of clarity of composition. Also, in order to avoid exaggeration, I used colors sparingly because I think they will have a stronger impact in their occasional presence.

Created using p5.js.

metadata.name: Mornings #19
metadata.description:
... a photograph taken at morning on a film camera somewhere in the American Midwest. The sun is present enough to light the sky, but still remains below the horizon leaving the land slightly underexposed and the trees nearly silhouetted ...

---

My journey continues to make the most compelling landscapes I can spring from a text editor. I spent a lot of time examining painted as well as traditional digital art landscapes, both of which are incredibly mature mediums. Paint, in particular, seems to be completely mastered - with some artist's work leaving nothing to be desired. What I have seen in digital has also blown me away. I want to work towards the bar set by these artists and marry their aesthetic prowess with the power, variety, and excitement of generative art.

--

// Technical Notes
-The render will take ~2-3 minutes.

-Default resolution is 3000x6000 px (including letterbox). While it's possible to render at any resolution, this is my intended resolution for the project - the product of an artistic choice to make the piece behave more like a photograph. This limited (but still high) resolution gives the features at the smallest scales some fuzziness, giving a sense that detail extends below the resolution of the piece. I think this imparts a more natural aesthetic as opposed to the perfect forms and edges of canvas shapes.


// Controls
Press "z" to zoom in, and take a look around. Keys "1", "2", "3", and "4" to control the zoom amount.

Press "s" to download the image. Right-click-save will not work.


// Owners
Token owners will have access to artist prints. Send me a DM on twitter.

metadata.name: Cs-55 #4
metadata.description:
Rutger Hauer; tears in rain; Vangelis' soaring soundtrack; Ridley Scott's grim, dystopian vision of Philip K. Dick's novel. I grew up with this, at a time when a movie making it onto television was a big thing. Over the years, I returned to the book and the film, craving subsequent movie cuts, working through K.W. Jeter's continuation of the tale, listening to Vangelis' extended soundtrack on a frequently-skipping early portable CD-player. And through those years, I've always wondered about the things that people wouldn't believe: the c-beams, glittering in the dark; the Tannhaüser Gate; and the attack ships, burning in space, just off the shoulder of Orion.

A canvas is split into regions, defined by a point and an angle. Across this canvas, random points are chosen, assigned values according to the number of regions in which they reside. Messy, splattered points are thrust into the void, forming a chaotic starfield of colourful beauty. And there, overlaid in scratchy, blur-smeared tracks, are the c-beams: atoms of Caesium-55 accelerated to near-light speeds, or so I'm told.

Monochrome variations exist, as do bright, colour-filled starfields. Lens flare and dark, polygon-based overlays mar infringe upon the background, casting shadow onto colour. Beam tightness and angle are variable; sometimes clustered into parallel streaks of light, sometimes a jumble of directionless light.

With thanks to Javier Graciá Carpio, whose works inspire and educate, and who revealed the secret of counting how many regions a point inhabits, albeit in a more confident and succinct manner than my own reinterpretation.

The render process is animated, but the piece is finished after precisely three hundred and sixty frames. Press [i] for just a little more information, and a few options for full-screen mode.

metadata.name: Methods of Dispersal #55
metadata.description:
We released the seeds at midday, following our best computer predictions, hoping against all odds that they'd travel far, re-seeding the earth, sowing a future for us.

It was months since the fall, since that terrible moment containment failed; quarantine failed; humanity itself failed. We called it ‘The Last Days’—unoriginal, perhaps, but descriptive all the same–and shook our heads in despair at our hubris, at the price we'd paid.

This would make it all right. Our computer model, proving we still had hope, that we'd make it all go away. The seeds would float on the wind, drifting into the tortured air, and carry with them new life.

And we would live again.
